Crimea and Sudetenland, same fight?
BRUSSELS – The takeover of Crimea by Russia is the gravest example of aggression in peacetime that Europe has known since the annexation of the Sudetenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is certainly customary today to downplay the importance of the "lessons of Munich" when mentioning this episode, which saw Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier give in to Hitler's demands on Czechoslovakia in order to appease the führer.
However, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of an invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, after the takeover of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might well regret their inaction.
Within Western capitals, the reactions have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered – an expulsion from the G8, for example – might seem amusing if the threat to peace in Europe wasn't so serious.
Putin considers the collapse of the Soviet Union to be the gravest catastrophe of the modern era, the man striving tirelessly to resuscitate a fallen Russian empire.
If the West wants to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination as Putin.
The numerous successes of the Russian president in the framework of his imperialist project have cost him almost nothing so far.
His initiative in favor of an Eurasian economic community has allowed him to rally to Russia a certain number of states rich in energy resources, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
The Georgia was dismembered in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation has pushed it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here is the most precious geostrategic trophy – Ukraine – which could fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "stops being an empire," as explained by former US National Security Adviser Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the other hand, with a suborned and subordinate Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the vast majority of Ukrainians aspire to nothing but join Putin's empire, it is highly likely that the country led by the Russian president will now be a highly militarized state, a sort of Soviet Union devoid of a communist party.
It is essential that the international community's reaction is commensurate with the degree of adventurism exhibited by Putin.
Annulations of summits, proposals of commercial agreements and other participations to as unproductive forums as the G8 cannot suffice.
Only moves involving the pronouncement of tangible economic sanctions, capable of affecting Russian citizens – who, let us recall, continue to re-elect Putin to power – will allow us to hope to see the Kremlin leave its expansionist trajectory.
Of what sanctions could it be?
First of all, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles Strait to Russian transports, as it did after the 2008 Russian-Georgian war.
In the past, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea in order to prevent the US from intervening, although it now appears clearly that it was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish Straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial ships heading towards Russian Black Sea ports.
The impact on the Russian economy – as well as on Putin's military claims – would be considerable.
Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the Montreux Convention of 1936.
Turkey could thus return to Putin the pretext invoked by him to justify the takeover of Crimea – namely that he would preserve the Russian ethnic groups living there – in asserting itself to protect its Turkish cousins of Tatar origin, who, given the bad treatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly want to remain under Ukrainian rule.
Last week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to make a U-turn in mid-air, in order to head towards Kiev to provide support to the new interim government.
The Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who like Putin is not tender, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish Straits to Russian transports – until Putin recalls all of his troops from Crimea so that they return to their bases, namely those in Sebastopol or Russia.
It would be good for Turkey to be able to count on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in the event that Russia tries to intimidate it.
Secondly, US President Barack Obama could enforce the same type of financial sanctions against Russia as he has imposed on Iran regarding its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed severely damaged Iran's economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the US financial system to all banks doing business with Russian banks or companies would allow for an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Citizens of Russia must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power was based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist approach could come at a great cost to them.
Thirdly, it would be possible for Obama to remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
A true drama in Putin's eyes, the disintegration of the Soviet Union has constituted for China the most formidable geostrategic windfall one can imagine.
In an instant, this empire that had ravished several million hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries, and threatened the People's Republic of nuclear annihilation, has simply vanished into thin air.
Since then, the independent states of Central Asia, and Ukraine itself, have become major commercial partners of China.
The invasion of Georgia by Russia has seriously displeased China, as was seen during the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held after the war (this regional grouping brings together a certain number of ex-Soviet states sharing borders with China and the motherland).
Russia had attempted to bring the SCO to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
However, the Organization had expressed its disagreement.
However, the Central Asian countries - Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan - would never have been able to rise up against the Kremlin without the support of China.
It now belongs to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's audacity.
The true test of this Chinese claim to be a true and responsible player in the international community will, however, soon take place at the United Nations.
Will China support this blatant violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it align itself in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other sanction options are also being considered.
Each Russian leader could thus have their visas refused or canceled.
It would also be possible to freeze a certain number of assets, particularly those that have been laundered by oligarchs close to Putin.
It is only when the pain becomes unbearable, and particularly for the elites, that this sort of kampf led by Putin today will fail.
The price of inaction may well be considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on the promise of America to take action firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Moreover, when Ukraine renounced its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the explicit condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) would guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one can blame Ukraine if it decides to re-nuclearize its defense (which it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous phrase "You had the choice between war and dishonor."
You have chosen dishonor, and you will have war." Obama and other Western leaders are today faced with a similar choice.
If they were to make the choice of dishonor, we can be certain that the audacious Putin will serve them a new war in the end.
